instructions: Adjust the machine so that you feel a good stretch in the starting position, slightly bent back. Then begin the movement by crunching forward, rounding your lower back a bit and squeezing your abs.
name: Ab Machine

instructions: Grab the ab roller and position yourself on the floor. Roll the ab roller away from you until your body is fully stretched out and then roll it back towards you so that you end up in the same position as you started in. Keep abs tight throughout the movement.
name: Ab Roller

instructions: No equipment is needed. Stand up straight and do a vacuum with your abs. Drag your stomach as far in as you can and keep it there for as long as you can. Once you let it back out you've completed one repetition.
name: Ab Vacuum

instructions: Stand up with one dumbbell in each hand. Keep your elbows tucked in at your sides and alternate between the dumbbells as you curl one at a time up. As you lower it down prepare to curl the other one up.
name: Alternating Dumbbell Curl

instructions: Grab a dumbbell in each hand and keep them at your sides. Alternate between them as you lift them forward until they're at shoulder height and then lower them back down.
name: Alternating Dumbbell Front Raise

instructions: Stand up with one dumbbell in each hand. Grab them as if you were grabbing two bottles so that your palms are facing inwards. Keep your palms facing inwards and alternate between the dumbbells as you curl one at a time all the way up, then lower it back down.
name: Alternating Dumbbell Hammer Curl

instructions: Stand with one dumbbell in each hand so that they are touching your sides. While keeping your arms almost straight, raise one dumbbell at a time to your side until it's just below shoulder level. Alternate arms between repetitions.
name: Alternating Dumbbell Side Raise

instructions: Grab a kettlebell in each hand at shoulder level. Alternate between them as you push one at a time over your head and then lower it back down until it's at shoulder level again.
name: Alternating Kettlebell Shoulder Press

instructions: While seated, position the dumbbells at shoulder level with your palms facing in. As you press the dumbbells up, rotate your arms so that your palms are facing outwards at the end of the movement.
name: Arnold Dumbbell Press (Seated)

instructions: Grab a kettlebell in each hand and position them at shoulder height just above your upper chest. Have your palms facing inwards, as you push the kettlebells over your head, rotate your arms so that at the end of the movement they're facing away from you. Then rotate them back as you lower the weight back down.
name: Arnold Kettlebell Press (Seated)

instructions: Hang freely from a pull-up-bar and have a friend stand behind you. Your palms should be facing inwards against you. As you begin to pull yourself up, have your friend assist you by pushing you up. Stop when your chins is above the bar and lower yourself back down.
name: Assisted Chinup

instructions: Hang freely from a pull-up-bar and have a friend stand behind you. Your palms should be facing forward, away from you. As you begin to pull yourself up, have your friend assist you by pushing you up. Stop when your chins is above the bar and lower yourself back down.
name: Assisted Pullup

instructions: Squat down and grab the medicine ball from the floor. As you stand up, throw it backwards over your head. Keep your back straight throughout the motion.
name: Backward Medicine Ball Throw

instructions: Lie down on a flat bench under a barbell. Preferably in a rack, for your own safety. Begin the movement by positioning your feet in the air and then lower the barbell down towards your chest. Then push it back up.
name: Barbell Bench Press (with Raised Feet)

instructions: Lie down on a flat bench under a barbell. Preferably in a rack, for your own safety. Begin the movement by unracking the barbell and lowering it towards your chest, once it hits the chest, push it back up. Consider using a spotter if you're lifting heavy weights.
name: Barbell Bench Press

instructions: Lie down flat on a bench with a barbell on the floor underneath the bench. Pull the barbell towards your abs and then lower it back down until it hits the floor again.
name: Barbell Bench Pull

instructions: Place a wooden block on the floor in front of you, unrack the barbell so that it is resting on your upper back and step up on the block with feet shoulder width apart, toes pointing slightly out. Keep your knees stationary as you raise your heels as high as you can and hold it for a second, then lower your heels back until you feel a full stretch of your calf muscles. Pause for a second in the bottom position of the movement to avoid using the achilles heel (bouncing back up).
name: Barbell Calf Raise

instructions: Stand over a barbell with feet flat on the floor. Grab the barbell with a shoulder wide grip and pull the bar off the floor up to shoulder height. Keep your back straight and abs flexed throughout the movement.
name: Barbell Clean

instructions: Sit on a bench with a barbell in front of you on the floor. Support your elbows with your inner thighs as you curl the barbell all the way up. Then lower it back down.
name: Barbell Concentration Curl

instructions: Stand up and grab a barbell at a shoulder width grip. Keep your elbows tucked in at your sides as you curl the barbell up until it reaches shoulder level, then lower it back down to your thighs.
name: Barbell Curl

instructions: Stand up straight with a barbell resting on the floor just in front of you. Squat down and grab onto the bar just outside of your thighs, flex your abs and arch your back, then simply stand up. The bar should follow your thighs along the way.
name: Barbell Deadlift

instructions: Stand up straight with a barbell resting on the floor just in front of you. Squat down and grab onto the bar just outside of your thighs, flex your abs and arch your back, then simply stand up. The bar should follow your thighs along the way.
name: Barbell Deadlift

instructions: Stand up in a rack or between two blocks, with the barbell placed slightly above the height of your knees. Bend forward over the barbell with a straight back and grab it with a shoulder wide grip, this will be your starting position. Thrust your hips forward and stand up straight with the barbell, don't overextend your back at the top. Lower the weight back down, you've just done a repetition!
name: Barbell Deadlift (from Block/Rack)

instructions: Stand up straight with a barbell resting on the floor just in front of you with desired chains on the sides of it. Squat down and grab onto the bar just outside of your thighs, flex your abs and arch your back, then simply stand up. The bar should follow your thighs along the way.
name: Barbell Deadlift (with Chains)

instructions: Lie down flat on the floor. Have a barbell either with weight plates on so that it is elevated or some objects at the sides that it can rest on. Get in under it and simply push it up, and then lower it back down.
name: Barbell Floor Press

instructions: Position the barbell on your upper chest and grab it with your palms facing upwards. Squat down until your legs are parallel to the floor and then stand back up. Keep your back straight and abs flexed throughout the movement.
name: Barbell Front Squat

instructions: Position the barbell just behind your legs. Squat down and grab it at a shoulder wide grip. Stand up with the barbell and then lower it back down to the floor. Keep your back straight and abs flexed throughout the movement.
name: Barbell Hack Squat

instructions:
Stand over a barbell with your feet slightly wider than hip width apart. Squat down and grab the bar with a little wider than shoulder width overhand grip. Arch your back and keep your arms completely straight.

Pull the bar off the floor by extending your hips and knees, as it reaches your knees, quickly raise your shoulder while keeping the bar close to your thighs. Jump upwards, fully extending your body and flexing your elbows out to the sides and pulling the bar to neck height. Then let it back down to the floor by bending your knees and lowering it to mid-thigh height and then slowly lower it to the floor with your back straight.
name: Barbell High Pull

instructions: Put the barbell on your upper back to start with. Take one step forward, landing on the heel of your foot and lower your body until your lowered leg almost touches the floor. Then stand back up. Switch used leg between repetitions. Keep your back straight and abs flexed throughout the movement.
name: Barbell Lunge

instructions:
The power clean can be split up into 4 steps.

1. The first pull - Floor to thighs
Stand behind the bar with your feet parallel and at hip width apart, shins touching the bar. Keep your arms straight and lower back in its natural arch, bend your knees slightly as you bend over the bar, grab it at a shoulder wide overhand grip.

Begin the movement by pushing through your heels as you simultaneously push your knees back, raise your chest and drive your hips forward as you lift the bar to just above your knees.

2.The transition
If you have lower back pain you can start the exercise from this position. Continue pulling the bar upwards until it's at level with the middle of your thigh. With your weight on your heels, get ready to aggressively push against the floor and extend your hips as if you were to jump up in the air.

3. The second pull - From hips towards your shoulders
From the transition position, quickly and powerfully thrust your hips forward and up, straighten your knees and extend your ankles, as if you were to jump straight up off the floor. Keep your arms straight and as you feel the bar gaining momentum, fully shrug your shoulders as quick as you can. As the bar rises, bend your elbows and raise them up as if you were doing an upright row. The bar should be moving up by itself from the momentum and you should only have to pull it with minimal force.

4. The catch - Catch the bar on your shoulders
As the bar is about to reach its maximum height, quickly pull your body underneath it, resulting in a squat position. Simultaneously rotate your elbows forward and under the bar so that your grip on the bar loosens as your wrists turn upwards. Catch the bar on the front of your shoulders and once you're stable, stand up straight. Congratulations, you've performed a power clean!
name: Barbell Power Clean

instructions: Start off by having the barbell at shoulder height resting on your upper chest. Then dive down by bending your knees slightly and then as you straighten your knees back, push the weight up in a straight line above your head. Then lower it back down.
name: Barbell Push Press

instructions: Start off by having the barbell rest on your upper back as if you were doing a Squat. Dive down by bending your knees slightly and as you stand back up, push the weight up in a straight line above your head. Then lower it back down.
name: Barbell Push Press (Behind the Neck)

instructions: Grab a barbell and bend over with a straight back. Pull the weight towards your shoulders and lower it back down.
name: Barbell Rear Delt Row

instructions: Stand up with a barbell resting on your upper chest. Keep your abs flexed and back straight as you press the weight straight up above your head, and then lower it back down.
name: Barbell Shoulder Press

instructions: Sit on a bench with the barbell resting on your upper chest. Keep your abs flexed and back straight as you press the weight straight up above your head, and then lower it back down.
name: Barbell Shoulder Press (Seated)

instructions: Stand up and grab a barbell at a little wider than shoulder width grip. Shrug the weight up and then lower it back down so that your arms are fully stretched. Try not to bend your arms as you do the movement.
name: Barbell Shrug

instructions: Grab a barbell at a little wider than a shoulder width grip behind you. Simply shrug the barbell up and then lower it back down until your arms are fully stretched. Try not to bend your arms as you do the movement.
name: Barbell Shrug (Behind the Back)

instructions:
With the bar on the floor in front of you, crouch down and grab it with a wide grip with the hands near the ends of the bar. Push off through your toes and slowly transition the weight to the middle of your foot. When the barbell is at mid-thigh height, extend your hips, knees and ankles so that your body is fully erect at the same time as you shrug the bar.

Continue the movement from the shrug by pulling the bar up so that it ends up above you, with your arms straight and slightly pointed outwards.

"Catch" the bar by squatting down while keeping your arms locked. You should end up in the bottom position of a Overhead Squat. Finish the movement by keeping your arms locked and standing up from the squat position.
name: Barbell Snatch

instructions: Put the barbell on your upper back and squat as far down as you can. Then stand back up. Keep your back straight and abs flexed throughout the movement. ATG stands for "Ass to Grass".
name: Barbell Squat (ATG)

instructions: Put the barbell on your upper back and squat down until your thighs are parallel to the floor. Then stand back up. Keep your back straight and abs flexed throughout the movement.
name: Barbell Squat

instructions: Place a bench behind you as if it was a chair. Put the barbell on your upper back and squat down until you sit down at the edge of the bench. Then stand back up. Keep your back straight and abs flexed throughout the movement.
name: Barbell Squat (to Bench)

instructions: Position a chair behind you and have a barbell resting on your upper back. Squat down until you are seated on the chair and then stand back up. Keep your back straight and abs flexed throughout the movement.
name: Barbell Squat (to Chair)

instructions: Position yourself under the barbell so that it's resting on your upper back. Squat all the way down until your legs are parallel to the floor and then stand back up. Keep your back straight and abs flexed throughout the movement.
name: Barbell Squat (with Chain)

instructions: Put a flat bench in front of you and have a barbell rest on your upper back. Step up on the bench with one leg at a time and alternate used leg between repetitions. Keep your back straight and abs flexed throughout the movement.
name: Barbell Step-Ups

instructions: Sit on a bench with a barbell positioned above your head. Keep arms straight at the start of the movement and begin by bending your arms at the elbow. Lower the weight down until it reaches your neck, then push it back up.
name: Barbell Triceps Extension (Seated)

instructions: Sit and grab the barbell with an underhand grip. Rest your arms on your thighs and let it roll all the way out to your fingers. Then squeeze it with your fingers so that the barbell ends up in the middle of your palm again.
name: Barbell Wrist Curl

instructions: Grab each end of a heavy rope anchored at it's center 4-5 meters (15-20 feet) away from you. Stand up tall and start off the movement by raising one arm to shoulder level as fast as you can, as you let the arm drop down again - raise the opposite side arm. Continue alternating arms like this until you're done.
name: Battling Ropes

instructions:
You will perform 5 exercises sequentially.

1. Power Clean
2. Front Squat
3. Push Press
4. Back Squat
5. Push Press

The combination of the 5 movements is one repetition.
name: Bear Complex

instructions: Place two benches near each other so that your feet are on one of them and your are at the other. Palms should be facing downwards and toes up. Lower your body with your arms until your elbows are parallel to the floor and then push yourself back up.
name: Bench Dip

instructions: Put a flat bench in front of you. Explode by pushing through your heels and jump up on the bench.
name: Bench Jump

instructions: Put a flat, high bench in front of you. Explode by pushing through your heels and jump up on the bench.
name: Bench Jump (High)

instructions: Grab a barbell with a little wider than a shoulder width grip. While keeping your back straight and abs flexed, bend over until your back is at a 45 degree angle towards the floor. Pull the barbell towards your abs and stop when they touch, then let the barbell back down so you end up with your arms fully stretched out.
name: Bent-Over Barbell Row

instructions: Put a pair of dumbbells on the floor in front of you on the floor. Position your feet at hip width apart, slightly bend your knees, bend over with a straight back, and grab both dumbbells with a neutral grip. Pull both dumbbells towards the side of your abs and then slowly let them back down until your arms are straight.
name: Bent-Over Dumbbell Row

instructions: Sit down on at the end of a flat bench and have a pair of dumbbells in front of you on the floor. Bend over so that your chest is touching your thighs and grab the dumbbells. Raise them to your sides until your arms are parallel to the floor, then lower them back down to the starting position.
name: Bent-Over Dumbbell Side Raise (Seated)

instructions: Place a kettlebell in front of you on the floor and grab onto a bench or a handle at same height as your hips. Bend over forward and grab the dumbbell with one arm and pull it up towards your abs. Then lower it back down until your arm is fully stretched.
name: Bent-Over Kettlebell Row

instructions: Rest your torso on the padding and grab onto the handles. Unrack the weight and lower the weight so that your arms are fully stretched. Then begin the movement by pulling straight towards your torso, slightly arching your lower back and pulling your shoulder blades together. Try to imagine that you're pulling with your back rather than your arms.
name: Bent-Over Machine T-Bar Row

instructions: Grab a dumbbell in each hand and bend over. Pull the dumbbells out to your sides until your arms are at shoulder level, and then lower them back down.
name: Bent-over Side Raise

instructions: Put a barbell on the floor against the wall with one end and stand over it so that the other end goes between your legs. Have a V handle attached to the end of the barbell. Bend over and grab it with both arms and pull the weight towards your abs, then lower it back down. Keep back straight and abs flexed throughout the movement.
name: Bent-Over T-Bar Row

instructions: Lie flat on your back and have your legs in the air. Imagine that you are on an upside down bicycle and begin to pedal. Optionally you can touch left elbow to right knee and the opposite.
name: Bicycle Crunch

instructions: Adjust the seat of the bike and start paddling.
name: Biking Indoors

instructions: Hit the road with your bike.
name: Biking Outdoors

instructions: Lay down flat on the floor with your legs bent. Thrust your hips towards the ceiling as far as you can and keep it in the top position for a second or two. Then release it back down to the floor again. You've just completed a repetition.
name: Bodyweight Bridge

instructions: Begin the exercise by taking a big step forward with one leg at a time, lowering your body against the floor in each step until your rear knee almost touches the floor. Then raise your body back up and return to your starting position, swap leg for your next step.
name: Bodyweight Lunge

instructions: Squat down until your legs are parallel to the floor. Then stand back up. Keep your back straight and abs flexed throughout the movement.
name: Bodyweight Squat

instructions: Put a flat bench in front of you. Step up on the bench with one leg at a time and alternate used leg between repetitions. Keep your back straight and abs flexed throughout the movement.
name: Bodyweight Step-Ups

instructions: Stand inside a Rickshaw Box and squat down to grab the handles at your sides. Keep your chest up and hips low as you start the movement. Begin pulling the bar up by standing up, pushing your hips forward and raising your back up until you are standing up straight. Avoid rounding the back throughout the movement, the key is to synchronize your hip and back movement so that neither does more work than the other.
name: Box Deadlift

instructions: Place a flat bench behind you and grab a pair of dumbbells. Extend one leg back at a time and place the top of the foot on bench. Squat down until your rear knee almost touches the floor, return to starting position. Keep your torso upright throughout the movement and swap to opposite leg after you're done with your repetitions.
name: Bulgarian Split Squat

instructions: Stand in a cable machine with opposite handles in each arm at shoulder level. Keep your arms in a straight line in front of you and then begin to drag the handles to your sides until your elbows are in line with your body. (90 degrees)
name: Cable Back Fly

instructions: Sit on a bench with a cable handle in between your legs. Grab it with one hand at a time and curl it all the way up, then lower it back down.
name: Cable Concentration Curl

instructions: Stand in a cable machine with one handle in each hand. The handles should be at shoulder height while hanging freely. Begin to pull them together as if you were hugging a tree with them. You should end up with the handles in front of you at chest level. Then finish the movement by letting them back out to your sides until your arms form two "L"s.
name: Cable Crossover (with High Angle)

instructions: Stand in a cable machine with one handle in each hand. The handles should be at knee height while hanging freely. Begin to pull them together and up as if you were hugging a tree with them. You should end up with the handles in front of you at chest level. Then finish the movement by letting them back out to your sides until your arms form two "L"s.
name: Cable Crossover (with Low Angle)

instructions: Stand in a cable machine with one handle in each hand. The handles should be at the same level as your chest while hanging freely. Begin to pull them together as if you were hugging a tree with them. You should end up with the handles in front of you at chest level. Then finish the movement by letting them back out to your sides until your arms form two "L"s.
name: Cable Crossover (with Straight Angle)

instructions: Stand on your knees in a cable machine with a cable attached to the handle. Grab the cable with both hands at the sides of your head. Pull the cable down as if you were doing an upside-down sit-up. Then let the cable back up. Keep hips stationary throughout the movement.
name: Cable Crunch

instructions: Stand up right next to a cable machine with a bar attached to it. Grab it and keep your elbows tucked in to your sides, then simply curl the weight up to shoulder level. Lower it back down slowly until your arms are fully extended.
name: Cable Curl

instructions: Grab the cable with both hands pointing in towards each other. Keep your back straight and elbows tucked in at your sides and begin the movement by curling the weight up to shoulder level. Pause for a second and lower it back down until your arms are fully extended.
name: Cable Curl (With Hammer Grip)

instructions: Stand in a cable machine with a rope or bar attached to the handle and have it at shoulder height. Begin the movement by pulling the handle towards your face and slowly let it back once it almost reaches your face.
name: Cable Face Pull

instructions: Stand in a cable machine and grab the handle near one of your sides at a time. Pull it forward until it's at shoulder height and then lower it back down.
name: Cable Front Raise

instructions: Stand up in a cable machine and replace the handle with a rope. Grab the rope as if you were grabbing a bottle and curl it up. Then lower it back down.
name: Cable Hammer Curl

instructions: Stand in a cable-machine and hitch a padded handle to your ankle. Push your used leg backwards as if you were curling it up. Then let it back down again.
name: Cable Leg Curl

instructions: Lie down flat on a bench with a cable handle beneath your head. Grab onto the handle with both hands and push it upwards so that it ends up above your chest. Then lower it back down until your triceps are fully stretched out.
name: Cable Lying Skull Crusher

instructions: Stand in a cable machine and have the handle behind you, above your head. Grab the handle and push it forward until your arms are fully stretched. Then lower it back so that it ends up behind your head again.
name: Cable Overhead Pushdown

instructions: Sit down on a bench with back support. Have the cable handle behind your head and grab it so that your palms are facing the same direction as you.
name: Cable Overhead Pushdown (Seated)

instructions: Stand in a cable-machine with a wide bar attached to the handle near the top. Pull your shoulders back and down and stand slightly bent forward. Grab the bar with a little wider than shoulder wide grip with your palms facing down. While keeping your arms straight, pull the bar down and in towards you until it touches the top of your legs. Then slowly let it back.
name: Cable Pullover

instructions: Kneel down on the floor in a cable machine and have the handle at shoulder height. Grab it with both hands so that your palms are facing inwards and tuck your elbows in at your sides. Push it down towards your thighs and then slowly let it back up.
name: Cable Pushdown (Kneeling)

instructions: Stand in a cable machine with a bar attached to the handle. The handle should be at shoulder height. Grab it with overhand grip so that your palms are facing downwards towards the floor. Tuck your elbows in at your sides and push the bar down towards your thighs, then lower it back up.
name: Cable Pushdown (with Bar Handle)

instructions: Stand up in a cable machine with a rope attached to the handle. The handle should be at shoulder height. Grab it with both hands to that your palms are facing inwards against each other. Tuck your elbows in at your sides and push the rope down towards your thighs, then lower it back up.
name: Cable Pushdown (with Rope Handle)

instructions: Bend over and grab opposite cable handle in each hand. Begin to pull them to your sides in line with your shoulders until your arms are at shoulder level.
name: Cable Rear Delt Fly

instructions: Stand in a cable machine with the handle at shoulder level. Pull it towards your shoulders and let it back.
name: Cable Rear Delt Row

instructions: Sit down on a bench in front of a cable machine. Pull the handle towards your lower belly while keeping your back straight. Then slowly let the handle back and let your arms stretch out fully.
name: Cable Row

instructions: Sit on a bench with back support and grab one cable handle in each hand at shoulder height. Start off by pushing the handles straight up above your head and then lower them back down.
name: Cable Shoulder Press (Seated)

instructions: Sit down on a bench without back support in the middle of a cable-machine. Begin the movement by grabbing both handles and pushing straight up above your head. Then lower the handles back down until they're at shoulder height.
name: Cable Shoulder Press (Seated, without Back Support)

instructions: Stand up and grab a cable handle. Raise it to your side until your arm is at shoulder level.
name: Cable Side Raise

instructions: Sit on a bench and grab a cable handle. Pull it out to your side until your arm is at shoulder level, and then lower it back down.
name: Cable Side Raise (Seated)

instructions: Stand in the middle of a cable machine with the handle attached to the top of it. Grab it with both hands and pull it diagonally down to the other side, try to pull with your abs rather than your arms. Then slowly return it to its starting position.
name: Cable Windmill

instructions: Sit and grab the cable handle with an underhand grip. Rest your arm on your thigh and let it roll all the way out to your fingers. Then squeeze it with your fingers so that the handle ends up in the middle of your palm again.
name: Cable Wrist Curl

instructions: Stand in a calf machine with the shoulder pads just above your shoulders. Begin the movement by standing up so that you have the weight on your shoulders, then raise your shoulders up as if you were to touch your ears with them. Then lower your shoulders back down.
name: Calf Machine Shrug

instructions: Stand in a dip station or between two steady bars. Grab the bars so that both your palms are facing inwards against you and begin the movement by lowering yourself down until your elbows are at shoulder level. Then push yourself back up.
name: Chest Dip

instructions: Hang freely from a pull-up-bar with a little less than a shoulder width grip. Your palms should be facing inwards against you. Pull yourself up until your chin is above the bar. Then lower yourself back down until your arms are fully stretched. See Weighted Chins if you are using extra weights.
name: Chinup

instructions: Just like a regular pushup except that you will explode on the way up so that your upper body is in the air for some time. While in the air, clap your hands together once and then quickly return them to their starting positions so that you land safely.
name: Clap Pushup

instructions:
Stand over a barbell with your feet positioned slightly wider than your shoulders. Squat down and grab the barbell with an overhand grip at a little wider than shoulder width. 

Pull the bar up from the floor by extending your hips and knees. As the barbell reaches shoulder level, pull your body in under the bar so that it is resting on your upper chest and your palms are facing upwards. Then bend knees slightly and drop your body down and split (one leg forward and one leg backward) and push the bar over your head. You can imagine that you're tucking your body in under the bar, straightening your arms and lastly standing up with the barbell.
name: Clean and Jerk

instructions: Lie down flat on a bench positioned in a rack with a barbell. Grab the barbell with a narrow grip. Lower the barbell down and tuck your elbows in at your sides. When it reaches your chest, push it back up until your arms are straight.
name: Close-Grip Barbell Bench Press

instructions: Stand up and grab a barbell at a little less than a shoulder width grip. Keep your elbows tucked in at your sides as you curl the barbell up to shoulder level. Then lower it back down to your thighs.
name: Close-Grip Barbell Curl

instructions: Lie down flat on a bench with two dumbbells resting on your chest. Position yourself under them so that your arms are straight. Begin the movement by lowering them towards your chest and tuck your elbows in at your sides. When they reach your chest, push them back up until your arms are straight.
name: Close-Grip Dumbbell Bench Press

instructions: Stand up with one dumbbell in each hand resting on your thighs. Your arms should be in front of you and your elbows supported by your thighs. Then curl the dumbbells up until they're at shoulder level and lower them back down.
name: Close-Grip Dumbbell Curl

instructions: Lie flat on a bench with a Ez-Bar resting on top of your chest. Grab the Ez-bar at the inner handles and push it up to starting position and tuck your elbows in at your sides. Lower it all the way down to your chest and then push it back up.
name: Close-Grip EZ-Bar Bench Press

instructions: Hang freely from a pull-up-bar with a little less than a shoulder width grip. Your palms should be facing forward, away from you. Pull yourself up until your chin is above the bar. Then lower yourself back down so that your arms are fully stretched.
name: Close-Grip Pullup

instructions: Just like a regular pushup but you will have a very narrow grip so that your fingers are touching each other. Lower yourself down and push yourself up.
name: Close-Grip Pushup

instructions: Lie down flat on your back and try to reach the ceiling. Identical to a sit-up but you will only raise your upper body upwards rather than sit up.
name: Crunch

instructions: Lie down on a swiss ball with your legs bent and places so that they're slightly pointing out from your body. Then lower your upper body so that it rolls over the ball, this will be your starting position. Keep your hands behind your neck for support, and push your upper body straight up towards the ceiling, flexing your abs. Hold at the top position for a second and then lower yourself back down to the startposition.
name: Crunch with Swiss Ball

instructions: Lie down on a decline bench in a rack, have a spotter unrack the barbell for you and keep it straight above your chest with arms straight; this will be your starting position. Lower the barbell to your lower chest, pause for a second and push it back up.
name: Decline Barbell Bench Press

instructions: Lie down on a declined bench with one dumbbell in each hand. Get the dumbbells in position above your chest and then begin the movement by lowering them down towards your lower chest. Then push them back up. Tip: Kick the dumbbells up to starting position with the help of your thighs.
name: Decline Dumbbell Bench Press

instructions: Lie down on a declined bench with one dumbbell in each hand with a hammer grip, i.e., your palms should be facing inwards towards each other. Get the dumbbells in position above your chest and then begin the movement by lowering them all the way down towards your lower chest. Then push them back up. Tip: Kick the dumbbells up to starting position with the help of your thighs.
name: Decline Dumbbell Bench Press (with Hammer Grip)

instructions: Lie down on a declined bench with one dumbbell in each hand resting at your lower chest. Begin the movement by pushing them up to the starting position with your arms straight. Then begin to lower them out to your sides until your elbows are at the same level as your body, then push them back together. Tip: Squeeze your chest together at the top of the movement as if you were squeezing a football!
name: Decline Dumbbell Fly

instructions: Lie down on a declined bench with two dumbbells resting on your chest. Push the dumbbells up to their starting position when your arms are straight. Your palms should be facing inwards against each other. Begin the movement by lowering them down behind your head until your triceps are fully stretched, then push them back up.
name: Decline Dumbbell Triceps Extension

instructions: Identical to the normal pushup. Technique is the same, the big difference is that you will keep your feet on an elevated bench and your hands on the floor. The bench should be just as high as a normal chair. Then lower yourself down towards the floor and push yourself back up.
name: Decline Pushup

instructions: Form a diamond on the floor in front of you with your hands, do this by bringing your hands together so that the tops of your index fingers meet and edges of thumbs also meet. Then lower yourself down as you would in a regular pushup and then push yourself back up.
name: Diamond Pushup

instructions: Put two benches parallel to each other so that you can place your hands on one and still reach the other with your feet. With your palms facing down and your feet on the other bench, lower yourself down as far as you can without feeling a strain on your shoulders. Try not to flare your elbows out as you go down. Then push yourself back up.
name: Dip (with Benches or Chairs)

instructions: Grab a ring in each hand and jump up so that your arms are extended and locked out. Begin the movement by lowering yourself down by flexing your elbow, stop when you break 90 degrees and push yourself back up. Avoid swinging and keep elbows close to your body throughout the movement.
name: Dip (with Olympic Rings)

instructions: Put something on the floor so that you can stand on it with the front of your foot as if you would be doing a regular calf raise. Grab onto something and bend over slightly, then begin the movement by pushing yourself up with one foot at a time. Lower yourself back down as far as you can and repeat.
name: Donkey Calf Raise

instructions: Put an object on the floor in front of you and that you can do calf raises off. Squat down and let your friend jump up on your back and then regain the balance. Step up on the object and begin doing calf raises, pushing yourself and your buddy as far up as you can. Then lower back down until you feel a good stretch in your calves.
name: Donkey Calf Raise (with Person on Back)

instructions: Lie flat on a bench and hold onto it at the sides near your head. Lift your lower body straight up in the air so that the only part touching the bench is your upper back and head, then lower it back down. Tip: Turn the movement around just before your legs touch the bench at the end of the movement.
name: Dragon Fly

instructions: Lie down on a flat bench with one dumbbell in each hand. Get the dumbbells in position above your chest and then begin the movement by lowering them down towards your chest. Then push them back up. Tip: Kick the dumbbells up to starting position with the help of your thighs.
name: Dumbbell Bench Press

instructions: Lie down on a flat bench with one dumbbell in each hand with a hammer grip i.e., your palms should be facing inwards towards each other. Get the dumbbells in position above your chest and then begin the movement by lowering them all the way down towards your chest. Then push them back up. Tip: Kick the dumbbells up to starting position with the help of your thighs.
name: Dumbbell Bench Press (with Hammer Grip)

instructions: Stand up with one dumbbell in each hand. Have a plate or some elevated object on the floor in front of you. Stand on it with the front of your foot and push yourself up through your foot. Then lower yourself back down. Tip: Stop for 1 second at the bottom of the movement.
name: Dumbbell Calf Raise

instructions: Sit on a bench with one dumbbell on the floor in between your legs. Grab it with one arm at a time and curl it up while supporting your elbow with your inner thigh.
name: Dumbbell Concentration Curl

instructions: Sit on a bench with one dumbbell on the floor in between your legs. Grab it with one arm at a time as if you were grabbing a bottle. Curl it up and then lower it back down.
name: Dumbbell Concentration Curl (with Hammer Grip)

instructions: Stand up with one dumbbell in each hand. Keep your elbows tucked in at your sides as you curl the dumbbells up until they're at shoulder level. Then lower them back down to the sides of your thighs.
name: Dumbbell Curl

instructions: Sit on a bench with back support. Grab one dumbbell in each hand and curl them up to your sides. Then lower them back down.
name: Dumbbell Curl (Seated)

instructions: Have two dumbbells on the floor just beside you and squat down to pick them up. Your stance should be shoulder wide as if you were doing a regular squat. Grab the dumbbells, flex your abs and arch your lower back and then stand up straight.
name: Dumbbell Deadlift

instructions: Lie down flat on the floor with one dumbbell at each of your sides. Get the dumbbells in position above your chest and then lower them down towards your chest, then push them back up. Hint: If you're using heavy dumbbells you can kick them up using your thighs.
name: Dumbbell Floor Press

instructions: Lie down on a regular bench with one dumbbell in each hand. Get the dumbbells in position above your chest and then begin the movement by lowering them out to your sides. You can imagine yourself hugging a giant tree on the way up, and then letting go as you lower them down. Go all the way down until your elbows are at the same level as your body. Tip: Squeeze your chest together at the top of the movement as if you were squeezing a football!
name: Dumbbell Fly

instructions: Stand up and grab a dumbbell in each hand. While keeping your arms straight, lift the dumbbells forward until they're at shoulder level, then lower them back down.
name: Dumbbell Front Raise

instructions: Stand up with one dumbbell in each hand. Grab them as if you were grabbing two bottles so that your palms are facing inwards. Keep your palms facing inwards and curl the dumbbells all the way up, then lower them back down.
name: Dumbbell Hammer Curl

instructions: Sit on a bench with back support. Grab one dumbbell in each hand with a grip as if you were holding a bottle, palms facing inwards. Curl the dumbbells all the way up and then lower them back down.
name: Dumbbell Hammer Curl (Seated)

instructions: Kneel down on a bench with one leg and keep the other one on the floor. Grab a dumbbell with one arm at a time and tuck your elbow in at your side. Then "kick" it back by lifting it up behind you. Finish the movement by lowering the weight back down. Tip: Bend slightly forward so that your upper arm is a little angled upwards.
name: Dumbbell Kickback

instructions: Grab a dumbbell in each hand and begin the movement by taking one step forward. Land on the heel of your foot and then lower your body until your lowered leg almost touches the floor. Then stand back up. Switch used leg between repetitions. Keep your back straight and abs flexed throughout the movement.
name: Dumbbell Lunge

instructions: Rest your chest against the preacher pad. Grab one dumbbell at a time and lower it all the way down until your arm is fully stretched and then curl it back up.
name: Dumbbell Preacher Curl

instructions: Sit in the preacher bench with one dumbbell in each hand. Your upper arm should be at the top of the bench, with the dumbbells facing each other (hands pointed inwards). Begin the movement by lowering them down simultaneously until both arms are fully stretched, then curl the weight back up. Keep palms facing inwards throughout the movement.
name: Dumbbell Preacher Curl (with Hammer Grip)

instructions: Lie down on a flat bench with a dumbbell resting on your chest. Push it up with both hands and begin to lower it behind your head until your arms are fully stretched. Tip: Keep shoulders tucked in and shoulder blades pulled back throughout the movement for better stability.
name: Dumbbell Pullover (Targeting back)

instructions: Lay down on a flat bench with a dumbbell resting on top of your chest. Grab it with both arms, palms facing upwards. With your arms straight and shoulders down, begin lowering the dumbbell over and behind your head as far as comfortable. Then lift it back up until it's above your chest. Remember to flex your chest throughout and really squeeze it at the top of the movement.
name: Dumbbell Pullover (Targeting Chest)

instructions: Grab a dumbbell in each hand and bend over with a straight back. Pull the dumbbells towards your shoulders and lower them back down.
name: Dumbbell Rear Delt Row

instructions: Grab a dumbbell in each hand. While keeping your legs and back straight, begin the movement by bending forward and lowering the dumbbells down. Lower them all the way down until your back is parallel to the floor or as far as you can.  Keep abs flexed throughout the movement.
name: Dumbbell Romanian Deadlift

instructions: Stand up with a dumbbell in each arm. Swing them up to shoulder height and have your elbows pointed straight out to your sides. Begin the movement by pressing the dumbbells straight up simultaneously until your arms are straight. Then finish it off by bringing them back down to shoulder height.
name: Dumbbell Shoulder Press

instructions: Sit on a bench with one dumbbell in each hand at shoulder level. Press the dumbbells up over your head and then lower them back down until they're at shoulder level again.
name: Dumbbell Shoulder Press (Seated)

instructions: Stand up and grab a dumbbell in each hand. Shrug them up to your sides and then lower them back down until your arms are fully stretched. Try not to bend your arms as you do the movement.
name: Dumbbell Shrug

instructions: Grab a dumbbell and let it rest at your side, touching your thigh. Begin the movement by lowering the dumbbell down along your thigh and bending your upper body to the side. Then stand back up straight. Alternate arm and side after you've performed all repetitions for one side.
name: Dumbbell Side Bend

instructions: Stand with one dumbbell in each hand so that they are touching your sides. While keeping your arms almost straight, raise the dumbbells up to the sides until they are just below shoulder level.
name: Dumbbell Side Raise

instructions: Sit on a bench and grab a dumbbell. Pull it out to your side until your arm is at shoulder level, and then lower it back down.
name: Dumbbell Side Raise (Seated)

instructions: Grab one dumbbell in each hand and squat down until your legs are parallel to the floor. Then stand back up. Keep your back straight and abs flexed throughout the movement.
name: Dumbbell Squat

instructions: Put a flat bench in front of you and grab one dumbbell in each hand. Step up on the bench with one leg at a time and alternate used leg between repetitions. Keep your back straight and abs flexed throughout the movement.
name: Dumbbell Step-Ups

instructions: Stand up with one dumbbell in each hand and get them to their starting positions right above your head by swinging them up. Your arms should be straight and pointing up. Slowly begin to lower them straight back with your elbows stationary throughout the movement. Lower them until they're at shoulder height. Then press them back up.
name: Dumbbell Triceps Extension

instructions: Lay down flat on the floor with a pair of dumbbells resting behind you. Grab them so that your elbows are both pointing towards the ceiling, this will be your starting position. Simultaneously press them up towards the ceiling until your arms are straight, then finish the movement by lowering them back down to the floor, stopping just before they touch it. Keep your elbows close to your body and don't let them flare out through the movement.
name: Dumbbell Triceps Extension (Floor)

instructions: Sit down on a regular bench with or without back support. Grab a pair of dumbbell and put them above your head so that your arms are straight. Begin the movement by lowering them back until they reach shoulder height, then push them back up until your arms are straight.
name: Dumbbell Triceps Extension (Seated)

instructions: Sit and grab a dumbbell with an underhand grip. Rest your arm on your thigh and let the dumbbell roll all the way out to your fingers. Then squeeze it with your fingers so that the dumbbell ends up in the middle of your palm again.
name: Dumbbell Wrist Curl

instructions: Get ready for a regular chin up, but instead of pulling yourself up you will jump up so that you're at the top position and start off the movement by slowly lowering your body back down.
name: Eccentric Chinup

instructions: Just like a regular Pull-Up but instead of pulling your weight up you will start off by jumping up to the top position of the movement. Then lower yourself down slowly.
name: Eccentric Pullup

instructions: Stand in the machine with a straight back and position yourself so that your weight is evenly distributed in your feet. Grab the handrails and begin striding forward or backward depending on your preference. Keep going continuously until you are done.
name: Elliptical Trainer

instructions: Rest your chest against the preacher pad. Grab an Ez-bar at the inner handle, your arms should be slightly rotated inwards from this grip. Lower the weight down until your arms are fully stretched and then curl the weight back up.
name: EZ-Bar Preacher Curl

instructions: Grab a dumbbell in each hand and begin walking. If you're in a gym with limited space you can put a dumbbell on the floor a couple of meters ahead and walk towards it and back as many times as you want. The dumbbells should be heavy enough so that you can only walk back and forth a couple of times and barely be able to hold onto them once you're done.
name: Farmer's Walk (with Dumbbells)

instructions: Grab a weight plate in each hand so that you're holding it with your fingers only. Begin to walk and hold onto the plate for as long as you can.
name: Farmer's Walk (with Weight Plate)

instructions: Lie down flat on a bench with a barbell lying just behind you. Grab onto it with a shoulder wide grip and remember to keep your upper arms locked throughout the movement. With the weight pressed straight up above you, begin the movement by slowly letting the barbell push your forearms down behind your head until they're fully stretched. Then press the weight back up. Keep in mind that the weight should come down behind your head and not towards your head.
name: French Press

instructions: Grab a dumbbell and position it at the same height as your shoulders. Hold it with both hands and begin to squat down until your legs are parallel to the floor. Then stand back up. Keep your back straight and abs flexed throughout the movement.
name: Goblet Squat

instructions: Place yourself under the barbell so that it is resting on your upper back. Keep everything stationary and begin to bend over, keeping your abs flexed. Stop when your torso is parallel to the floor and return to upright position.
name: Good Mornings

instructions: Sit down on a bench with a barbell resting on your upper back. Bend over as far as you can, or until your torso is parallel to the floor. Then sit back up. Keep your back straight and abs flexed throughout the movement.
name: Good Mornings (Seated)

instructions: Start the movement by positioning yourself against a wall in a handstand. Lower yourself down until your head just barely touches the floor or slightly above, and then push yourself back up.
name: Handstand Pushups

instructions: Hang freely from a pull-up-bar and raise your legs straight forward as if you were doing a curl with your whole body.
name: Hanging Leg Raise

instructions: Hang freely from a pull-up bar with your feet together. Raise them up to the starting position with your knees bent so that it looks like you're sitting in a chair. Begin the movement by pulling your legs further up so that you almost touch your shins with the bar above you. Then lower your legs back down to the sitting position and repeat.
name: Hanging Pike

instructions: Lie down on an inclined bench under a barbell. Preferably in a rack for your own safety. Then un-rack the barbell and begin to lower it towards your upper chest. Then push it back up. Consider using a spotter if you're lifting heavy weights.
name: Incline Barbell Bench Press

instructions: Lie down flat on an incline bench with a barbell on the floor beneath the bench. Pull the barbell towards your abs and then lower it back down until it hits the floor again.
name: Incline Barbell Bench Pull

instructions: Lie down on an incline bench, facing away from the cable machine. With a straight bar attached to the cable machine, lie down on the bench and grab it with an overhand grip so that your palms are facing up. This will be your starting position. Keep your elbows locked as you push the bar forward until your arms are fully straight, then let it back to the starting position.
name: Incline Cable Triceps Extension

instructions: Lie down on an inclined bench with one dumbbell in each hand. Get the dumbbells in position above your chest and then begin the movement by lowering them down towards your upper chest. Then push them back up. Tip: Kick the dumbbells up to starting position with the help of your thighs.
name: Incline Dumbbell Bench Press

instructions: Lie down on an inclined bench with one dumbbell in each hand with a hammer grip, i.e., your palms should be facing inwards towards each other. Get the dumbbells in position above your chest and then begin the movement by lowering them all the way down towards your upper chest. Then push them back up. Tip: Kick the dumbbells up to starting position with the help of your thighs.
name: Incline Dumbbell Bench Press (with Hammer Grip)

instructions: Sit on an incline bench with a dumbbell in each hand at arms length. Curl one dumbbell up at a time by lifting your forearm up, the upper arm should be stationary throughout the movement and your palms facing forward. As you reach shoulder level with the dumbbell, begin to slowly lower it back down until your arm is fully stretched, then repeat with other arm. That is one repetition.
name: Incline Dumbbell Curl

instructions: Lie down on an inclined bench with one dumbbell in each hand. Get the dumbbells in position above your chest and then begin the movement by lowering them out to your sides. You can imagine yourself hugging a giant tree on the way up, and then letting go as you lower them down. Go all the way down until your elbows are at the same level as your body. Tip: Squeeze your chest together at the top of the movement as if you were squeezing a football!
name: Incline Dumbbell Fly

instructions: Lie down on an incline bench with a dumbbell in each hand straight above your chest. While keeping your elbows locked, begin to lower them down behind your head as far as you can and then bring them back up.
name: Incline Dumbbell Triceps Extension

instructions: Identical to the normal pushup. Technique is the same, the big difference is that you will keep your hands on an elevated bench rather than the floor. The bench should be high enough that you get a good angle from the floor. Then lower yourself down towards the bench and push yourself back up.
name: Incline Pushup

instructions: Have a barbell in a rack and lie down beneath it so that you barely can reach it. Grab it at a shoulder width grip with your palms facing forward away from you. Pull yourself up against the bar until your chest almost touches it. Then lower yourself back down until your arms are fully stretched again.
name: Inverted Bodyweight Row

instructions: Lie down flat on the floor with your arms fully extended behind your head. Begin the movement by bending at your waist, lifting your legs up at the same time as you reach for your toes with your arms. Ending up looking like a  jackknife in the finishing position. Then lower legs back down and extend your arms again prior to the next repetition.
name: Jackknife Situp

instructions: Position the barbell on the floor so that one end is behind you and the other end is in front of you. Grab it in front of you with one hand and behind you with the other. Stand up and then squat back down until the barbell touches the floor, or your legs are parallel to the floor. Keep your back straight and abs flexed throughout the movement.
name: Jefferson Squat

instructions: Grab a kettlebell in each hand and position them at shoulder height just above your upper chest. Simply push them up over your head until your arms are fully stretched and then lower them back down.
name: Kettlebell Overhead Press (Seated)

instructions: Stand up straight holding a kettlebell. Let it hang freely between your legs and then begin the movement by swinging it up to your side until it reaches head height. Switch sides between repetition.
name: Kettlebell Pirate Ships

instructions: Grab a Kettlebell in each hand at shoulder level. Let them rest on your upper chest and then push them up over your head. Lower them back down until they are at shoulder level again.
name: Kettlebell Shoulder Press

instructions: Grab a pair of kettlebells and keep them at your sides so that your palms are facing inwards. Pull your shoulders back and down, keep your shoulder blades and abs tight throughout. Simply shrug the kettlebells up, squeeze for a second, and then lower them back down until both arms are fully extended. Make sure to not roll your shoulders, they should just be moving up and down in a straight line.
name: Kettlebell Shrug

instructions: Stand up with a kettlebell on the floor slightly in front of you, in between your legs. Bend your knees and grab onto it with an overhand grip while keeping your shoulders pulled back. Simply stand up and make sure your knees don't 'fall in' as you do it. Sit back down until the kettlebell almost touches the floor again, that's one repetition.
name: Kettlebell Squat

instructions: Position yourself under a barbell so that it is resting on your upper back, holding it with a wide grip. Keep your body tight and press the weight straight up until your arms are straight. Lower it back down and slightly bend your knees as it comes down on your upper back to share the load.
name: Klokov Press

instructions: Place a box at your side and explode through your heels and jump up on it.
name: Lateral Box Jump

instructions: Lie down flat on a bench. Grab a barbell at a shoulder wide grip. Position yourself under the barbell so that it is above your chest. Bend your elbows but keep them stationary and lower the barbell down behind your head until your triceps are fully stretched. Then push it back up so that it ends up above your chest.
name: Lying Barbell Skull Crusher

instructions: Lie down flat on a bench with two dumbbells. Position yourself under the dumbbells so that they're above your chest. Begin the movement by bending your elbows and lowering the dumbbells behind your head until your triceps are fully stretched. Then push them back up so that they end up above your chest.
name: Lying Dumbbell Skull Crusher

instructions: Lie down flat on the floor and grab onto something behind your head if needed. Lift your legs all the way up so that they are pointing towards the ceiling, and then lower them back down so that they touch the floor.
name: Lying Leg Raise

instructions: Lie down at your side and grab a dumbbell with the arm furthest up. Position the dumbbell near your hip and raise it straight up until your arm is straight, and then lower it back down.
name: Lying Side Raise

instructions: Lie down on a flat bench with one dumbbell resting on your chest. Lift it up to starting position with both hands so that your arms are straight and the dumbbell is above your chest. Then lower it behind your head until your triceps is fully stretched, using one arm at a time. Push it back up to starting position.
name: Lying Single-Arm Dumbbell Triceps Extension

instructions: Lie down flat on an incline bench with a barbell on the floor beneath the bench. Place a V handle at the end of the barbell and grab onto it. Pull it towards your abs and then lower it back down until it hits the floor again.
name: Lying T-Bar Row

instructions: Grab onto the handles and keep your elbows tucked in at your sides. Begin the movement by pulling downwards with your abs, slightly rounding your lower back in the movement.
name: Machine Ab Crunch

instructions: Adjust the machine so that the handles are at the same height as the lower parts of your chest. Pull your shoulder blades together and push the handles forward until your arms are fully stretched. Come back slowly until the handles are
name: Machine Bench Press

instructions: Sit in the machine and grab the handles. Simply curl them up while trying to keep your elbows as stationary as you can.
name: Machine Biceps Curl

instructions: Sit on the machine with the cable adjusted at its highest level. With a slight bend at your knees begin pulling towards your face until your upper arms form a T with the cable. Then lower it back down while keeping your upper body stationary.
name: Machine Cable High Row

instructions: Sit on the machine with a slight bend in your knees. Bend over forward to grab the handles and sit up straight. While keeping your upper body stationary, pull the weight towards your abs and then return it back to the starting position.
name: Machine Cable Low Row

instructions: Sit down in a bench press machine. Rather than pushing with your heels, put your feet at the bottom part of the plate so that only the upper part of your feet are touching it. Push through your toes and then lower the weight back down. Tip: Stop for 1 second at the bottom of the movement.
name: Machine Calf Press

instructions: Stand up in the machine with the pads on your shoulders, unrack the weight and lower it all the way down so that you feel a good stretch in your calves. Push it all the way up and then lower it back down slowly, pausing at the bottom for a second or two to avoid pushing with your achilles heel.
name: Machine Calf Raise

instructions: Sit down with the pads on your upper thighs and unrack the weight. Lower it all the way down so that you feel a full stretch of your calves, then push it all the way up and return back down. Pause for a second or two in the bottom of the movement so that the weight doesn't get pushed up with the help of your achilles heel.
name: Machine Calf Raise (Seated)

instructions: Sit in a dip machine with the paddings above your thighs for support. Grab onto the handles at your sides and begin pushing down.
name: Machine Dip

instructions:
Machines can differ from each other but in general you should adjust the seat so that you're seated with your back against the padding and have the handles just below shoulder height. 

Grab onto them and push them in towards each other as if you were hugging someone in front of you. Pause when the handles reach each other and then slowly return them back to the starting position.
name: Machine Fly

instructions: The technique is identical to a regular Squat, but with extra stability from the machine. Stand in the machine with the shoulder pads on your shoulders, unrack the weight and sit down until your thighs are parallel to the floor, then stand back up.
name: Machine Hack Squat

instructions: Sit in the machine and grab the handles with your palms facing inwards against you. Simply curl them up while trying to keep your elbows as stationary as you can.
name: Machine Hammer Curl

instructions: Place yourself in a hyperextension machine and adjust it so that the pads end at your hips. Bend over until your lower back is fully stretched and then come back up. If you need more resistance you can hold onto a weight plate or a dumbbell.
name: Machine Hyperextension

instructions: Adjust the machine so that your legs fit comfortably under the rack. Grab the bar and sit down with your legs under the rack. With a slight arch in your lower back begin pulling down towards your upper chest. After touching your chest with the bar, slowly return it until your arms and lats are fully stretched.
name: Machine Lat Pulldown

instructions: Sit in a pulldown machine but rather than pulling towards your upper chest, pull the bar towards your neck. Stopping just before it touches it.
name: Machine Lat Pulldown (Behind the Neck)

instructions: Sit down in the machine and grab the handles at your sides. Place the padding just below your calves so that your legs are fully extended for the starting position. Curl them down until you have a 90 degree angle at your knee and then return back to the fully extended position.
name: Machine Leg Curl

instructions: Adjust the machine so that you're sitting comfortably and the seat ends just before your knee. Fully extend your legs while keeping the rest of your body stationary, then lower them back down to the starting position.
name: Machine Leg Extension

instructions: Sit down in the machine and put your feet up against the plate as if you were doing a Squat. Unrack the weight and lower it down until your knee is at a 90 degree angle, then push it back up. Stop just before your legs are fully straight to relieve your knees from extra stress.
name: Machine Leg Press

instructions: Lie down on the machine with the pads just below your calves and grab onto the handles at your sides. While keeping your upper legs static, curl the weight up as far as you can and keep your upper body stationary. Then lower the weight back down until your legs are fully stretched.
name: Machine Lying Leg Curl

instructions: Sit comfortably in the machine with your upper arms resting against the padding. Grab onto the handles and curl the weight all the way up, and then lower it back down slowly until your arms are fully stretched.
name: Machine Preacher Curl

instructions: Sit in the machine and adjust the pad so that you can reach the handles while your chest is pressed up against it. Grab the handles and begin pulling back. Try to keep your elbows as close to your sides as possible and imagine that you're pulling with your elbows, not your arms. Once you've reached as far back as you can go, slowly begin to let the handles back until your arms are fully stretched. Repeat.
name: Machine Row

instructions: Adjust the machine so that the handles are just below shoulder height. Grab them and begin pushing straight up, then lower them back down to the starting position.
name: Machine Shoulder Press

instructions: Sit down in the machine with your shoulder blades squeezed together. Raise your shoulders as far up as you can and hold it for a couple of seconds. Then lower them back to the starting position.
name: Machine Shrug

instructions: Adjust the machine so that you're sitting comfortably and the seat ends just before your knee. Fully extend you leg while keeping the rest of your body stationary, then lower it back down to the starting position. Alternate leg when you've finished the desired number of repetition.
name: Machine Single-Leg Extension

instructions: Lie down in a leg curl machine but only use one leg when curling the weight up. Alternate leg after you've finished your desired amount of repetitions.
name: Machine Single-Leg Lying Curl

instructions: Sit comfortably in the machine and begin the movement by pushing your legs out to your sides as far as you can. Then return them to the starting position. All of this while keeping your upper body stationary.
name: Machine Thigh Abduction (Out)

instructions: Sit in the machine and adjust it so that you feel a minor stretch as you put your legs into the starting position. Push your legs together and then slowly let them back out again until you return to the starting position.
name: Machine Thigh Adduction (In)

instructions: Sit in the machine and grab the handles. Pull them downwards as far as you can and then return them to their starting position slowly.
name: Machine Triceps Extension

instructions: Adjust a pulldown machine and replace the bar with a V-Bar. Grab onto it and pull down towards your upper chest and then slowly let it back up until your arms are fully stretched.
name: Machine V-Bar Lat Pulldown

instructions: Lie down flat on the floor with a medicine ball at your side. Grab the ball and move it to your other side. Repeat.
name: Medicine Ball Twist

instructions:
An overhead squat is a simple squat with the bar over your head. Unrack the bar and have it resting on your upper back, in a bouncing move, push the bar up above your head and lock your arms. This will be your starting position.

Lower the weight by bending your knees until your thighs are parallel to the floor. Then push the weight back up. Your back should be straight throughout the movement.

Use lighter weights until you have learned the proper form.
name: Overhead Barbell Squat

instructions: Lie flat on the ground and put your elbows down so that your standing on them and your toes. Keep back and abs tight and hold the position for as long as you can.
name: Plank

instructions: Hang freely from a pull-up-bar with a little wider than shoulder width grip. Your palms should be facing forward, away from you. Pull yourself up until your chin is above the bar. Then lower yourself back down until your arms are fully stretched. See Weighted Pull-Ups if you are using additional weights.
name: Pullup

instructions: A simple pushup. Lie down on the floor and push yourself up. Can be done on the knuckles if you feel wrist pain.
name: Pushup

instructions: Grab a barbell with a reverse grip at shoulder width so that your palms are facing inwards against you. Let the barbell rest against your thighs at the bottom of the movement, then curl the weight up until it's at shoulder level. Lower it back down.
name: Reverse Barbell Curl

instructions: Like a regular crunch, but reversed. Lie flat on your back and begin the movement by raising your legs up in the air, pulling them towards your face. Then lower them back down until your knees are back at a 90 degree angle. Keep your arms at your sides for balance throughout the movement.
name: Reverse Crunch

instructions: Grab a barbell with a reverse grip at a little narrower than shoulder width. Bend over forward until you're torso is parallel to the floor and pull the barbell towards your abs. Then lower it back down until your arms are fully stretched.
name: Reverse-Grip Bent-Over Barbell Row

instructions: Stand up in a cable-machine and grab the handle with a reverse grip so that your palms are facing upwards. Pull the weight down towards your thighs and then lower it back up.
name: Reverse-Grip Cable Pushdown

instructions: Sit on a bench with one dumbbell on the floor in between your legs. Grab it one arm at a time with a reverse grip and curl it up while supporting your elbow with your inner thigh.
name: Reverse-Grip Dumbbell Concentration Curl

instructions: Rest your chest against the preacher pad. Grab one dumbbell at a time with a reverse grip. Begin the movement by lowering the dumbbell all the way down until your arm is fully stretched and then curl it back up.
name: Reverse-Grip Dumbbell Preacher Curl

instructions: Rest your chest against the preacher pad. Grab the Ez-bar with a reverse grip on the outer handles. Your palms should be facing down against the floor. Begin the movement by lowering the bar all the way down until your arms are fully stretched, then curl it back up.
name: Reverse-Grip EZ-Bar Preacher Curl

instructions: Lie down flat on a bench in a rack. Grab the barbell with a reverse grip at a little wider than a shoulder width. Lower the weight towards your chest and then push it back up.
name: Reverse-Grip Triceps Bench Press

instructions: Place yourself in a roman chair with your elbows on the support pads. Begin the movement by raising your legs until they are parallel to the floor then lower them back down.
name: Roman Chair Leg Raise

instructions: Just like a regular roman chair lift except that you will keep your legs closer to your body rather than straight. This will make it much easier and you can use this exercise to work your way up to fully straight legged roman chair lifts.
name: Roman Chair Leg Raise (Easier)

instructions: Have a barbell on the floor in front of you. With legs straight and abs flexed, reach down and grab it at a shoulder wide grip. Stand up straight with the barbell in your hand. Finish the repetition by lowering it back down to the floor.
name: Romanian Deadlift

instructions: Grab the rope and begin climbing. Try not to use your legs.
name: Rope Climb

instructions: Grab the rope and climb until you reach the top.
name: Rope Climb (with Leg Assist)

instructions: Attach the rubber band to something stable at shoulder height. Grab onto the rubber band with both hands at a ltitle wider than shoulder wide grip, begin the movement by pulling it towards your face and slightly up, stopping just before reaching your face. Then let it back until both of your arms are extended again. Keeping your shoulder blades back throughout the movement lets you better target the rear delts.
name: Rubber Band Face Pull

instructions: Get on the treadmill and begin running.
name: Running on Treadmill

instructions: Find a route to your liking and begin running. If you are new into running focus on keeping a good tempo rather than sprinting.
name: Running Outdoors

instructions: Stand up with a kettlebell on the floor in front of you. Bend over and grab it with both of your hands while keeping your back in its natural arch. Thrust your hips forward and swing it up until it reaches head height. Your upper arms should be relaxed throughout the movement and your neck in its natural position. Let the kettlebell fall back down and once your elbows and upper arms touch your sides, begin to bend over again to catch the kettlebell in between your legs.
name: Russian Swing

instructions: Lie down on the floor with a weight plate of desired weight beside you. Sit up as if you were doing a sit up but keep your legs slightly in the air and then begin the movement by grabbing the weight plate with both hands and moving it from side to side just above your abs.
name: Russian Twist

instructions: Grab onto the Rubber-Band with one arm at a time just above your hips. Your arm will look like an L, with the upper arm being tucked in to your side and the lower arm pointing straight forward. Begin the movement by pushing your arm straight in towards your stomach and rotating at your elbow. Stop when you reach your stomach and slowly return to the starting position.
name: Shoulder Inward Rotation (with Rubber Band)

instructions: Grab onto the Rubber-Band with one arm at a time just above your hips. Your arm will look like an L, with the upper arm being tucked in to your side and the lower arm pointing straight forward. Begin the movement by pulling the rubber band straight out to your side while keeping your upper arm static. Go as far out as you can comfortably and then slowly return to starting position.
name: Shoulder Outward Rotation (with Rubber Band)

instructions: Two exercises in one for simple logging. Begin by doing Shoulder Innies, followed by Shoulder Outies. The exercises work the rotatorcuff and should be done with light weights. View Shoulder Innies- and Shoulder Outies- with Rubber-Band for exercise instructions.
name: Shoulder Rotation (Rotator Cuff)

instructions: Lie down flat on your back as if you were doing a regular crunch. Begin the movement by doing a crunch to one side, at the same time raising your knee up towards your face so that your shoulder almost touches it. Then lower back down so that you lie flat on the floor and repeat with the other knee.
name: Side Crunch

instructions: Lie on one side at a time. Put your elbow down so that your standing on it and the side of your foot. Keep your back and abs tight and hold the position for as long as you can.
name: Side Plank

instructions: Stand up in a cable machine and grab one handle at a time. Keep your elbow tucked in at your side as you curl the weight up. Once the handle reaches shoulder level, let it back down to your thighs.
name: Single-Arm Cable Curl

instructions: Stand in a cable-machine and grab the handle at shoulder height with one arm at a time. Push it down towards your thighs and keep your elbow tucked in at your side throughout the movement.
name: Single-Arm Cable Pushdown

instructions: Like a regular chin-up except that you'll use one hand at a time. Grab onto the pull-up-bar with your palm facing inwards against you and pull yourself up until your chin is above the bar. Then lower yourself back down.
name: Single-Arm Chinup

instructions: Sit down in the machine with your chest pressed up against the padding. Begin the exercise by grabbing onto one of the handles with a grip so that your palm is facing upwards and slightly arching your back. Pull the handle down to your side, and then slowly let it back up until your arm is straight.
name: Single-Arm Chinup in Hammer Strength Machine

instructions: Sit down on a bench with a dumbbell resting on your thigh, kick it back while you lie back on the bench and get it into it's starting position with the help of both arms. Stabilisize yourself and let go with the other arm, you will need to keep your abs tight to remain on the bench. Slowly lover the dumbbell down as far as comfortable and then push it back up. You may grab onto the bench with the other arm for support. Start very light to get used to the different kind of movement and slowly increase in weight over a couple of weeks to give your body a chance to get used to it.
name: Single-Arm Dumbbell Bench Press

instructions: Stand up and grab a dumbbell in each hand. While keeping your arms straight, lift the dumbbells forward until they're at shoulder level, then lower them back down.
name: Single-arm Dumbbell Front Raise

instructions: Sit on a bench with one dumbbell in each hand resting on your thigh. Get in the starting position by kicking them up with the help of your legs so that they end up at shoulder height. Begin the movement by pushing them straight up until your arms are straight. Then lower them back down to shoulder height.
name: Single-Arm Dumbbell Overhead Press

instructions: Sit on a bench with back support. Grab one dumbbell in each hand at shoulder level, push them up over your head and then lower them back down.
name: Single-Arm Dumbbell Overhead Press (Seated)

instructions: Place a dumbbell on the floor and position yourself over a bench with one knee on the bench and the other one on the floor. Bend over forward with a straight back, flex your abs and grab the dumbbell. Begin pulling it to your side towards your abs. Then lower it back down.
name: Single-Arm Dumbbell Row on Bench

instructions: Stand up with a dumbbell in your hand and swing it up to shoulder height. Your elbow should be pointing straight out to your side at the start position of the movement. Then begin by pressing the dumbbell straight up until your arm is straight. Finish the movement by slowly bringing it back down to shoulder height. Switch arm when you're done with your repetitions.
name: Single-Arm Dumbbell Shoulder Press

instructions: Stand up and grab a dumbbell. Position it at shoulder height then push it straight above your head so that your arm is straight. Keep the elbow stationary while you slowly lower the dumbbell back until it reaches shoulder height. Then push it back up. Switch hand after you've finished your repetitions.
name: Single-Arm Dumbbell Triceps Extension

instructions: Lay down flat on the floor with a dumbbell behind you. Grab it with one hand at a time, your elbow should be pointing towards the ceiling, this will be your starting position. Press it straight up until your arm is straight, then lower it back down until it almost touches the floor again. You've just completed a repetition. Switch hand when you've completed all repetitions with one hand.
name: Single-Arm Dumbbell Triceps Extension (Floor)

instructions: Sit down on a regular bench with or without back support. Grab a dumbbell in one hand and put it above your head so that your arm is straight. Begin the movement by lowering it until it reaches shoulder height, then push it back up until your arm is straight.
name: Single-Arm Dumbbell Triceps Extension (Seated)

instructions: Position the kettlebell on the floor and stand above it. Squat down and grab it with one hand at a time and swing it up so that it ends up at shoulder height with your palms facing upwards. Push it up in a straight line over your head and then lower it back down. The movement is finished when the kettlebell reaches the floor again.
name: Single-Arm Kettlebell Clean and Jerk

instructions: Start off the movement by holding the kettlebell at shoulder height just above your chest. Then dive down by bending your knees and shooting your hips backwards, then push your body up and straighten your arm. You should end up with the kettlebell straight above your head, then lower it back down to shoulder height.
name: Single-Arm Kettlebell Jerk

instructions: Grab a kettlebell and hold it at your side. Raise it out and up to your side until it's at shoulder level, then slowly lower it back down. Switch arm after you've done all repetitions.
name: Single-Arm Kettlebell Side Raise

instructions: Place a kettlebell on the floor between your feet. Squat down and pick it up with one hand at a time and begin the movement by swinging the kettlebell back behind you and then bring it back front and all the way up above your head.
